Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law introducing administrative liability for violating the terms and procedure for paying for goods (works, services) when making purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of state and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the General Prosecutor&#39;s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who entered into contracts that were not supported by financing, tried in every possible way to evade their payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment under public orders, the prosecutor&#39;s office has made 9.7 thousand submissions, based on the results of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary liability, 533 to administrative liability, to investigative bodies to organize procedural inspections, 75 materials were submitted, 46 of them criminal cases were initiated.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
Moreover, these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in paying services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts led to fabulous debts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the due money on time.
The result is a growing financial lump of debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not turned to the prosecutor&#39;s office for help.
Now in a number of regions the problem has been maximally leveled.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by the prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the prosecutor&#39;s office works in manual anti-crisis management.
The Prosecutor General personally conducts field meetings with representatives of local authorities, at which all violations discovered by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are substantively examined.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ &quot;On Amending the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offenses in the Part of Establishing Administrative Responsibility of the Customer&#39;s Officials for Violation of the Terms and Procedure for Payment for Goods (Works, Services) in Procurement to Ensure state and municipal needs&quot;, which was signed by the President of Russia last week.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General&#39;s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offenses of the Russian Federation with an article that provides for a fine of 30,000 to 50,000 rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the deadline and procedure for paying for goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, then he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
