Why are laws enforced in Singapore?
I&#39;m talking to local businessman Chang while I&#39;m sitting at an outdoor diner.
Commenting on the situation in Singapore, Chang smokes one cigarette after another, while carefully storing the cigarette butts in an iron box taken with him from the office.
After the end of the conversation, the businessman goes to the nearest urn - a hundred meters from it - and throws the bulls into it.
The fine for littering in a public place is 500 local dollars, Chung says.
You know, since childhood, I just developed a reflex: you can’t throw a candy wrapper on the pavement, you’ll be fined instantly.
Now there are video cameras everywhere.
And indeed - the sidewalks of Singapore in the city center are clean, like in a museum.
Chang says that three months ago, his neighbor&#39;s 18-year-old son graffitied the wall of an old colonial building.
The court found the guy guilty of vandalism and sentenced him to flogging.
What?!
Imagine.
He received ten blows to the buttocks with a wooden stick and spent a week in prison.
In general, corporal punishment is not uncommon.
How the highest standard of living and incredibly harsh laws are combined in Singapore, the AiF observer figured out on the spot.
Here, no one thinks of abolishing the death penalty, - explains lawyer Victor Li Hong.
And the government has long spit on the opinion of both the European Union and the United States on this matter.
If a person transports a large consignment of drugs or sells them, he is entitled to the gallows.
In 2002, a 22-year-old Australian citizen was detained at Changi Airport: he was carrying 400 grams of cocaine with him.
The Australian Prime Minister came to his defense, threatening sanctions, international human rights activists and even the Pope.
However, the guy was eventually hanged anyway.
After that, drug couriers diligently go around our country.
The point is this: in Singapore it is supposed that EVERYONE must comply with the laws, and not just modest and poor people.
It doesn&#39;t matter who you are - a millionaire, vice-premier, famous artist or a resident of the European Union.
There is only one option in this case: if they find a pound of cocaine on you, you will be hanged.
When you walk around Singapore and everywhere you meet signs with a bunch of warnings, you simply wonder how many prohibitions there are in this city-state!
For example, chewing gum is sold only in pharmacies, and you can buy it strictly by prescription (!) Of a doctor.
The gum will not be taken away from the tourist upon arrival, but it is worth sticking a &quot;gum&quot; in the subway, they will impose a fine of 1 thousand local dollars.
In four days, I met two people with white signs around their necks: &quot;I littered.&quot;
For a cigarette butt thrown past the urn, in addition to a fine, they are often sentenced to &quot;link to the janitors&quot;: they clean up parks and beaches for a week.
6 thousand rubles the &quot;criminal&quot; who forgot to flush the water in the public toilet pays, and when trying to relieve himself of a small need in the elevator of a residential building, a special detector is triggered - the doors are blocked and a signal is sent to the police.
Among the completely exotic laws are bans on feeding pigeons on the street, public performance of songs and even excessive watering of a houseplant (!): It is believed that the abundance of water attracts mosquitoes.
To avoid fires, smokers cannot carry lighters on the subway, otherwise they will be fined 5 thousand Singapore dollars.
In general, the thought appears: no matter how hard you try, you will definitely break something.
This is not so at all, - Mohammed Kabir-Kajaria, the owner of a local travel agency, is trying to dissuade me.
Particularly fantastic laws exist only on paper, and over the past twenty years I have not seen anyone prosecuted for violating them.
Why are they saved?
So that citizens do not relax.
Compliance with the basic rules is strictly monitored.
For example, if a minor is sold cigarettes in a kiosk, then everyone along the chain will be punished: the owner of the store will pay a huge amount, the violator himself will receive blows on the &quot;back&quot; with sticks, and the seller will also be whipped and sent to prison.
It is thanks to such harsh laws that offenses in Singapore are very rare.
Is it justified?
Back in the seventies, we had chaos on the roads - motorists ignored traffic lights, drove as they wanted, got behind the wheel drunk.
After the introduction of fines for the year, everything calmed down.
Now the driver, having drunk a portion of whiskey, knows: if they stop, the policeman will not let him go for a bribe, they will impose a fine in the amount of the cost of the apartment and send him to jail for years.
To many foreigners, the city-state in Southeast Asia seems like a kind of concentration camp.
In 1993, the American writer William Gibson called Singapore &quot;Disneyland with the death penalty&quot; - a visitor from the United States was horrified by the general wealth of the inhabitants, &quot;a frighteningly clean airport&quot; and &quot;cultivated nature.&quot;
They say that such things are unnatural, they look artificial, and in principle this should not be so.
The first days in Singapore and you are truly afraid to throw a piece of paper on the sidewalk, you remember if you went to the subway with ice cream.
But then you come to the &quot;Little India&quot; area, and suddenly there is a &quot;break in the pattern&quot;: plastic cups are lying around the bus stop.
&quot;How is it?&quot; - you are surprised.
And so, Singaporeans grin.
Anything happens.
Not every such &quot;crime&quot; will be caught on the spot, but you should know: if you are found out, you will not excuse yourself - after all, you have violated the law.
Most often, this is enough for a person to behave normally.
Of course, the government in Singapore is quite authoritarian.
But you know what?
In Vietnamese Ho Chi Minh City, I moved very carefully - motorcyclists often snatch smartphones and cameras from the hands of tourists.
The center of Paris is full of dirty homeless people and beggars.
On our streets, too, not everyone tries to throw garbage into the bins.
Singapore, thanks to a set of draconian fines and ruthless (up to the death penalty) laws, has become the calmest, cleanest and safest city on Earth.
Think about it.
Such is human nature: remember, in Russia, no one was wearing seat belts while driving until they began to fine.
Although the main thing in Singapore is not fines, but voluntary compliance with laws.
And one must think that in Russia, people would also be happy with clean streets, the absence of garbage in the subway and would welcome the arrest of those who confuse an elevator with a public toilet.
Here is corporal punishment - thank you, no need.
Otherwise, the laws of Singapore are at least worth looking at.
Nothing sacred?
Now the Trump White House has set its sights on the Statue of Liberty.
The surest sign of a regime change is when he starts fighting the statues.
Americans understand this as well as anyone else - hence the deliberately theatrical demolition of Saddam Hussein&#39;s statue in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration&#39;s key ideologues, no doubt knew what he was doing when he raised the symbolic ax over the Statue of Liberty during a heated argument with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president&#39;s proposals to drastically reduce legal immigration.
Let&#39;s be honest, Miller didn&#39;t attack the statue itself.
Hordes of pleasure boat owners and Statue of Liberty performers would lynch him if he tried.
But he attacked its meaning, and especially the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when poems by Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta: “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are referring to was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.&quot;
Miller got the facts right, but as he himself said, it&#39;s not really about history.
This is about the current sound of the startling words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state does not invite any immigrants, but the poorest: &quot;Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming of breathing freely, / The unfortunate dregs of your abundant shores.&quot;
Never before have &quot;unfortunate scum&quot; been so visible on our screens.
Miller was not engaged in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not expected in America.
This dispute over the meaning of the statue is part of a larger political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute over the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends, who fought to place her words on the statue&#39;s plinth after her death - knew very well that they were committing an entirely political act.
The sculpture was supposed to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Liberty.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she received a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of poem and image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, right though change it back.
The vociferous Rush Limbaugh, the sort of John the Baptist who heralded the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that Liberty invites no one, rather it is an early neocon bringing the flame of America to a world lying in darkness: “Liberty marches forward.
She carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the USA.&quot;
Against his wont, Limbaugh really hit the spot here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
It was Lazarus&#39; great creative achievement to see her the way haggard, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often difficult voyage would see her.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are looking for shelter and a chance at a better life.
Her statue answers them with words of hope and hospitality that they long to hear.
And, of course, this is not a prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to light the way, but to kindle hatred, which is the only source of their strength.
