Blocking critics on Facebook: Don&#39;t run for public office if you&#39;re not ready to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what the critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn&#39;t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said: &quot;You can take away the freedom of speech and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter.&quot;
I now turn to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan&#39;s subordinates blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor&#39;s subordinates called this suit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of &quot;so what.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s just Facebook,&quot; many will say.
But this is also important.
And that&#39;s especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He&#39;s a remarkably popular Republican governor in a predominantly Democratic state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a hardened reactionary.
He has demonstrated a firm hand in the management of the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as a primary way to connect with his constituents and jokingly shows off his chemo-bald head on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor&#39;s page - which is billed as an official public forum and run by administration officials with taxpayer money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor&#39;s actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply moderation.
But it&#39;s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters who are vicious on the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor who are talking to their elected leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, referring to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramana of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hate but asked about the hate crimes.
&quot;I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,&quot; she wrote in the comments section of the Post article.
&quot;I also don&#39;t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say that this is a so-called cheat, instead of admitting that they are dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.&quot;
What the governor&#39;s subordinates call a &quot;concentrated spam attack&quot; others would probably call &quot;an active lifestyle.&quot;
In the era of Facebook, it&#39;s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or deleting negative comments.
It&#39;s a much less dusty job than it used to be, when it required sending people in, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and gagging protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in numbers.
Haugen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casheris of Alexandria, the Chair of the Loudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning the voter from her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Gov. Matt Bevin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn&#39;t be that hard.
During the Washington era, the era of affordable postage was about as revolutionous as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800 the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the writers of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms &quot;Juricola&quot;, &quot;Valerius&quot;, &quot;Belizarius&quot; and &quot;Porcius&quot; wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington&#39;s decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was inundated with petitions attacking his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn&#39;t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means going along with it.
