When preparing dinner, Bardina Degei does not use the stove.
She rarely even uses the potty.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Panyai district in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just places a sweet potato, locally called &quot;nota&quot;, right on the hearth.
Half an hour later, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the dirt floor - she has no furniture - and it is here that she does her chores, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The latrine is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives and therefore was not assigned to work in the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many of the men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
This is a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by raising their hands in public in front of the occupying troops.
The existing independence movement from the Netherlands has quickly turned its ire against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the region, keeping out foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the capital of the province, to Nabire, and then a five-hour jogging in a hired car.
There is no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the corrugated steel roofs are rust-painted in a variety of reddish hues.
Few Indonesians made it here, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pagos of Papuans worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
“It was strange for us to wear these clothes,” says Degei, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia&#39;s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it is also the Indonesian land of gold.
The world&#39;s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is only sixty miles from Paniai, a highland province roughly the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves valued at $78 billion.
These riches, however, bring one misfortune to the Papuans, ensuring that the mighty Indonesian military maintains a stifling presence here.
Between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million, including up to $150,000 to one officer, according to a 2005 New York Times investigation.
Demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this gold mine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
More than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, according to human rights activists, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
&quot;We will lose everything,&quot; a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane contains testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture - rape and electric shocks are particularly frequent, another report alleges - and brutal repression of peaceful demonstrations.
&quot;It&#39;s hard to count the number of casualties because incidents happen every week,&quot; says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts were tightened as Papua&#39;s resources attracted an influx of migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The province&#39;s population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographics are shifting as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese stalls, &quot;warungs,&quot; sell fried chicken and &quot;gado-gado&quot; mixed vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Local residents are trying to withstand the competition.
“The migrants started selling chicken and vegetables at the traditional market for less than the natives of Papua,” explains Abet Yow, a 24-year-old Panyai native who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, for work.
&quot;Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua - the mother-mother (women) of Papua - have lost their market.&quot;
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua&#39;s 29 districts, including Paniai.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice,” Yow says.
In reality, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokowi Paniai experienced a tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols around a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle burst out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them that they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Jawedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers fired at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election commission building, and the situation escalated the next day.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought ritual hunting bows with them and performed the vaita, the dance of the Papuan mee pago tribe: they ran in circles and imitated bird singing.
Some protesters started throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
As the situation escalated, the order was given to the soldiers via intercom: &quot;If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,&quot; according to an official document seen by TIME magazine, but not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Eremias Kayame, head of the Kyogo Koto district in Enarotali, sensed the approach of danger and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
Nobody wanted to listen to him.
“As I turned around, my left wrist was suddenly hit by a bullet,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn&#39;t know who fired the shot, but says that the bullet came from the direction of the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
Local resident Alfius Yove was hit three times, according to his cousin who witnessed the shooting.
&quot;I ran up to him and looked at his body to make sure it was him,&quot; Yohanes, who like many Indonesians only goes by one name, told TIME grimly.
&quot;I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.&quot;
General Yotje Mende, Papua Police Chief Inspector, told reporters that his officers were only &quot;protecting&quot; their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pujo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
&quot;It&#39;s a matter of life and death.&quot;
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered an impassioned speech in Jayapura, expressing condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the issue of historic abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights violations.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
“Most of the violations happened long ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early zero.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed,” he said.
Wiranto then retracted his words when speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta and said he had no plans to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said: &quot;Everything will be decided through the courts.&quot;
Wiranto, who was accused by the United Nations of &quot;crimes against humanity&quot; in connection with the death of more than 1,000 people during the bloody vote for the independence of East Timor in 1999, said that 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the incident in Paniai.
The families of the victims in Paniai greeted such statements with grim disbelief.
“In the past three years, I have been asked four times, but there has been absolutely no change,” Johanes says.
&quot;I&#39;m tired&quot;.
He says he still lives in fear years later.
“I&#39;m scared,” he says.
“I am afraid that the military will arrest me, I am afraid that they will shoot me.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came for me,” he says.
The shooting didn&#39;t stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in the neighboring Deiyai district of Panyai.
A clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take the unconscious man to the hospital left one person dead and 17 others injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the construction site office owned by the company.
The villagers hurled stones at the officers, who fired warning shots in response, police said.
But local residents claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) began shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
&quot;We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retribution,&quot; Dominggu Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being rushed in, told TIME magazine.
&quot;I hid in my house for two days.&quot;
The Deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account and that the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development has angered the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout Papua&#39;s verdant central highlands.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of the Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and kidnappings against Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM&#39;s top leaders come from Paniai, including Thadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and groundlessly detained by the military in recent years in Paniai under the pretext of &quot;defending national independence&quot;.
Some never returned.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is considered a &quot;sad, forgotten place&quot;.
Poverty increases discontent.
The small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is equally inaccessible.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly nota, but also some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can tend four to five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the crop for the family and the rest is sold at the local market.
Ten nota tubers cost only IDR 10,000 (75 cents).
Over time, the economic disparity between the native Papuans and new migrants increased, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
The few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
The Papuans rarely have the money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive businesses.
“Young people don&#39;t want to stay in the village ... because there is no work or money here,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua off the radar of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudi and Basile Longchamp were deported from Papua for &quot;lack of coordination with relevant organizations&quot; despite being given rare filming permits.
Phelim Kine, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, said promises made during Jokowi&#39;s campaign to lift media restrictions to promote transparency and development have not been kept.
&quot;Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting,&quot; he said in a statement.
The lack of media attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to Papua&#39;s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate &quot;diverse and widespread violations&quot; in Papua, including the shooting in Panyai.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanata Nasir brushed aside the group&#39;s claim, telling reporters in Jakarta that &quot;Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so hiding evidence of episodes of human rights violations would be difficult.&quot;
The locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch Human Rights Ambassador Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, the locals broke their silence, pleading, &quot;We want freedom,&quot; according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but the Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
“Jokowi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of a threat from a greedy army, are mired in poverty, and their education and health care is in a miserable state.
Gobai says that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote given to Jokovi as a debt that he must pay.
&quot;They don&#39;t want money, they just want justice,&quot; he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out one last symbolic act of defiance: they buried the body of one of the victims on a piece of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not let the guilty forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus says without looking up.
&quot;What else were we supposed to do?&quot;
Fire engulfs Dubai&#39;s Torch skyscraper for the second time
A fire engulfed one of the world&#39;s tallest residential skyscrapers in Dubai on Friday, forcing hundreds of residents to flee the 337-metre-tall, 79-story structure.
This is the second fire to sweep through the high-rise building - coincidentally called The Torch - in two years.
The building was evacuated, no casualties were reported, and there was no operational news on the cause of the fire.
“We slept and woke up from the fire alarm and the screams of people.
We ran down the stairs and it took us about ten minutes to get down from the fiftieth floor,&quot; a skyscraper resident who identified himself as George told Reuters.
Fire brigades extinguished the fire at approximately 4:00 local time (00:00 GMT) and cooled the building, the Dubai Civil Defense Authority said.
The government said it was working to provide shelter for the victims.
The incident could bring the safety of materials used in high-rise building exteriors around the world back onto the agenda.
During the investigation by the Fakel administration after the fire there in 2015, it turned out that the cladding, the external panels used for decoration and insulation, suffered the most damage.
In the United Kingdom, police said they believe the insulation system and cladding at London&#39;s Grenfell Tower may have accelerated the spread of a fire there in June that killed about 80 people.
