EPA chief Pruitt abandons intention to delay implementation of Obama-era emission reduction rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to delay implementation of Obama-era regulations designed to reduce emissions of air pollutants and smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that his agency now listens more than in previous administrations to the needs of state environmental regulators.
He did not mention a lawsuit filed in federal appeals court against his previous position.
The dispute revolves around the October 1 deadline by which states must meet 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would delay compliance by one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid &quot;inconsistency with local decisions or impeding economic growth.&quot;
Pruitt, who was Attorney General of Oklahoma before being appointed by President Trump to his current position, has long been known as a staunch opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of regulations opposed by the chemical or oil and gas industries.
Wednesday&#39;s sudden change of course is yet another legal setback to Pewitt&#39;s return to normality course.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA had overstepped his authority in trying to delay the implementation of an Obama administration rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by making the abrupt change of course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling EPA&#39;s duty to work with states in a comprehensive process to meet the new standards on time.
&quot;Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others, and negotiated deadlines as the case progressed,&quot; said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous role.
&quot;We don&#39;t believe in regulation by litigation and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take our charter and the power it gives us seriously.&quot;
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point again use his &quot;powers to defer and other statutory powers&quot; to make sure the rules are &quot;jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information.&quot;
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of ozone regulations.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on this issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that filed a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
&quot;The EPA&#39;s change of course - following our lawsuits - is a major victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by smog in their cities,&quot; Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia joined the New York lawsuit.
Ground-level ozone is created when common pollutants from cars, power plants, refineries, chemical plants, and other sources react with sunlight in the atmosphere.
The resulting smog can cause severe breathing problems in sensitive individuals, resulting in thousands of premature deaths per year.
Public health and environmentalists hailed Pruitt&#39;s unexpected change of course.
&quot;It&#39;s sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from the person tasked with protecting the air we breathe,&quot; said Laurie Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
&quot;We must continue to resist the Trump administration&#39;s ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.&quot;
