A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past spectators in the village of Monroe, Georgia, and roared toward the small Morse Ford Bridge.
As the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its path.
The leader, a middle-aged man in a pinstripe suit, took a puff on his cigar and peered through the windshield.
Those inside were trembling with fear.
&quot;We need that nigga, Roger!&quot; the man barked.
&quot;Get him out of the car!&quot;
Shrill shrieks broke the silence as a young black man was dragged from the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene that played out on July 22 is just a dramatization.
But when a noose was thrown around the neck of &quot;Roger&quot;, almost all the spectators really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to re-enact the night that two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and May Murray Dorsey, were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
No one has been convicted of these murders.
&quot;It&#39;s amazing that in all these years not a single person has been arrested - although we see them next to us; although we know who they are,&quot; says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
&quot;It&#39;s a stain on our history and it&#39;s a stone on our souls.&quot;
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia congressman who has fought for human rights all his life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been corrected.
&quot;We want an investigation, we want a conclusion, we want a cure, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,&quot; he says.
&quot;We can&#39;t move on to healing and reconciliation until we get justice.&quot;
A coroner covers the body of one of the victims of the Morse Ford lynching with a sheet on July 27, 1946.
More than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of participating in the lynching, according to FBI files obtained by NBC News.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always known two related vigilante motives: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time permitted black citizens to vote in the primary that was to be held that summer.
Around the same election, according to the FBI, black sharecropper Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently over a woman.
Brooks says that rumors circulated around town that Hester slept with Malcolm&#39;s wife Dorothy, and that the child she was to have was not her husband&#39;s.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a large white landowner, paid $600 bail to get Malcolm out of jail, according to the FBI.
He went to jail with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they were driving out of jail and approaching the Morse Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
&quot;It turns out that Harrison organized and commanded the murders,&quot; such a conclusion is made in one of the FBI reports.
&quot;It is also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement who not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed evidence and covered up the identities of witnesses.&quot;
Brooks calls it shorter.
&quot;It was an attack on voting rights,&quot; he says.
&quot;They were all killed to send a message to black people in the city: if you register and vote, the same will happen to you.&quot;
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has directed an annual re-enactment of the Morse Ford Bridge lynching.
Her performance is graphic, it captures the viewer and tells about the deep racism that many would like to believe does not exist anymore in America.
It&#39;s hard to look at and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that&#39;s the point.
&quot;We don&#39;t want to talk about lynching because it shows us our own ugliness,&quot; she says.
&quot;But I can&#39;t build a relationship with you if you don&#39;t hear me or hear what I&#39;ve been through.&quot;
Rehearsals for this year&#39;s play began in June, and on the first day nearly 30 actors—a dozen whites, the rest blacks—gathered indoors and listened to a polished review of the play over the years.
Wade Marbo directed with Green.
He played the role of the main member of the clan for several years, but says that the role never got easier.
&quot;I feel like I&#39;m dirty because that&#39;s not the same person that I am,&quot; says Marbo.
&quot;But I think it&#39;s very important to remember this history because we don&#39;t want to go back to that time.&quot;
Indoors, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, reprise their roles.
The play begins with Malcolm, furious that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
&quot;I said nigga get out of my house!&quot;
Screaming Rascon in response.
There is a blow.
And at the same moment, everyone (at least all black actors) burst into laughter.
Greene laughs the loudest.
&quot;What is it?&quot; Ascona asks.
He is worried and confused.
Am I overplaying?
&quot;No,&quot; Green says through laughter.
&quot;I just don&#39;t think white people used to say &#39;nigga&#39; back then.&quot;
&quot;Yes, yes,&quot; one of the black performers laughs.
&quot;You must say a hard &#39;r&#39;.&quot;
And the energy in the room changes in the same way: discomfort is replaced by a sense of camaraderie.
Everyone must do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of the four murdered people.
The scene starts over.
This time, when Rascona says the &quot;n&quot; word, it comes out clear and sharp.
Not a single person laughs.
The play ends violently and quickly.
Screams, shots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday&#39;s sad song &quot;Strange Fruit&quot;.
Her voice breaks through a word.
A hundred yards away, fifty spectators are wiping tears and sweat from their eyes.
There is an almost equal number of blacks and whites among the audience.
One couple traveled from Ithaca, New York to watch the show; many live very close by.
They all endured the heavy heat of Georgia for nearly eight hours as Brooks took them on a pilgrimage to the graves of the Malcolms and Dorseys.
Up to this point, the murders were just history, but now, when they stand in the same place where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are right there in the air.
As the last note of the song fades, Green invites people to come closer and inspect the bodies.
Children bend down to their heads, touch the blood paint and motionless bodies, and whisper something to each other.
&quot;They&#39;re not truly dead,&quot; mutters one little boy, as if to remind himself of this.
A few minutes later, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly it&#39;s all over.
The actors drop the ropes from their necks and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the head Klansman.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the performance has finally fallen on him.
&quot;It&#39;s all right,&quot; one of the women whispers.
&quot;We know you have a good heart.
You had your reasons for doing it.&quot;
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta are animatedly discussing a play with a black couple they have just met.
Denise Daplinsky struggles to find words to describe how she feels after the performance.
&quot;It&#39;s hard to listen to these horrible, creepy words and actions... of people who look like you and who do it because they look like you,&quot; she says.
&quot;After that, I think lynchings still happen,&quot; she adds, &quot;only now it&#39;s called police shooting.&quot;
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks is in the spotlight as he reminisces about his work as a human rights activist over a meal.
He says he&#39;s already started planning next year&#39;s show.
&quot;The production inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we have experienced, but also teaches us,&quot; he says.
&quot;Because if you don&#39;t learn from this lesson, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it.&quot;
