PSG could certainly shell out to hire Neymar and add him to a galaxy of other stars, given the team&#39;s funding from Qatar&#39;s energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums to acquire players, but they have to balance it with legitimate sources of income in order to reach the profitability threshold in their football business.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA President in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that ran into huge debts in their pursuit of success were, in effect, cheating and risking ruin if banks or owners stopped funding.
In 2011, FFP stopped focusing on club debt and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model that Roman Abramovich had originally used at Chelsea in 2003 – to buy a club with good potential and then spend heavily to improve the team and create a global brand – has become a difficult plan.
During this three-year assessment period, which spans 2018, clubs could face losses of €30m.
And despite Platini&#39;s ignominious removal from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor Aleksandar Čeferin is still determined to curb overspending.
&quot;Of course the FFP is alive and we will tighten the rules as we move forward,&quot; Andrea Traverso, who controls the FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay the buyout of Neymar&#39;s contract at a time, they can distribute this amount over the entire term of his contract for reporting purposes.
Neymar signed a five-year deal, so the transfer fee can be shown in the annual accounts as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, PSG, as well as Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, were heavily sanctioned.
PSG were fined 60 million euros ($82 million at that rate), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and were ordered to limit their Champions League squad for the 2014-1015 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is tracking down clubs that might try to outwit its financial controls by inflating their income at the expense of companies linked to the club&#39;s owners.
Although the Qatari company could sponsor PSG, if the amount of funding was considered to exceed the standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to be considered legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014 when UEFA ruled that PSG&#39;s funding from the Qatar Tourism Authority had been inflated.
It has been reported that part of Neymar&#39;s earnings at PSG may have come in the form of payments from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will become a World Cup ambassador, and such a maneuver could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
Past sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be even more closely monitoring any attempts to circumvent the rules.
