They spoke with the Associated Press agency on condition of anonymity, as they are not authorized to discuss the position of PSG.
According to the latest published reports, in 2015-1016, PSG received more than 10 million euros in profit on a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The financial statements for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expect Neymar&#39;s arrival to be fertile ground for sponsorship deals, merchandise sales and team-branded T-shirts.
The club expects turnover to increase by at least 30 percent due to the hiring of a new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best players is leaving, the Spanish league tried to block the transfer of Neymar, saying that PSG would violate financial fair play.
&quot;This is a clear case of &#39;financial doping&#39;, with the club and the state,&quot; La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar as PSG&#39;s ultimate owner.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports mogul, shares La Liga&#39;s doubts about the club&#39;s state funding.
&quot;It&#39;s all equity and it&#39;s completely changed the landscape of football in the last fifteen years,&quot; Wenger said on Thursday.
“When the club belongs to the country, everything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to comply with financial fair play, because a country can have many paths and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The procedure and places for taking the oath will be determined by the President
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation, the president will determine - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Building.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath in law.
Children under 18 years of age, as well as those incapacitated, will be exempted from taking a solemn oath, follows from the finalized text of amendments to the bill &quot;On Citizenship of the Russian Federation&quot; (available to Izvestia), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
On June 6, President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of introducing an oath upon becoming a citizen of the Russian Federation instead of formally signing documents during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading in a bill providing for the abolition of the decision to grant citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet ( Part 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for hijacking an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if this act is related to terrorism (Part 4 of Article 211 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: when filling out documents for citizenship, a person signs a promise to comply with Russian legislation - by embarking on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The bill was submitted to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev (United Russia), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Fair Russia) and State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the procedure for taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law &quot;On Citizenship of the Russian Federation&quot;, indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where the coat of arms of the Russian Federation can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state authorities of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could be the registry offices.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will take a solemn oath after officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after he takes the oath, follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that they will swear allegiance to Russia from the age of 18, and not from 14.
The rule has been preserved according to which the incapacitated or partially incapacitated, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath with their own hands, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt &quot;other persons&quot; from this procedure.
Also, the updated bill spells out a special procedure for admitting residents of Ukraine to Russian citizenship, who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting an appropriate application to the authorized body of Ukraine for this.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The renunciation of &quot;foreign&quot; citizenship, as now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if this is impossible &quot;due to reasons beyond the control of the person.&quot;
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including First Vice Speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalya Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all United Russia).
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for a decision on their fate regarding the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the day before the head of the Duma Committee on State Building and Legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (ER).
In addition, a clarification appeared in the text that restrictions on holding certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who renounced their &quot;other&quot; citizenship in writing and handed over their previous passport to the Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs, but &quot;for reasons beyond his control&quot; it was not stopped be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are prohibited from holding positions in the municipal service, being hired at facilities and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country cannot become a State Duma deputy or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should come into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
Nostalgia becomes a niche in Hot American Summer and Fellow Detective
The current iteration of the story is nostalgically reminiscent of the characters&#39; glorious days in the 80s at the same time; about the grunge era in the 90s (around the time when masterminds David Wayne and Michael Schowalter made the sketch comedy The State for MTV); and about herself - that is, about 2001, before her stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler and Paul Rudd moved on to more serious things.
