The result doubles as a major joke: middle-aged actors play horny children who have just come of age; thanks to this, the inability to return to becomes part of the joke.
&quot;Ten Years Later&quot;, where adults played adults, has less deep emotional roots, and its parody is more haphazard and includes riffs from stalker films of the 90s like &quot;The Hand That Rocks the Cradle&quot;.
In one episode, a character pulls out an Apple Powerbook, four-wheel inline skates, and &quot;a bunch of other stuff from 1991.&quot;
Many of the plot lines are the same.
Good-natured Coop (Showalter), now a writer, still hasn&#39;t won over Kathy (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still hasn&#39;t lost his virginity.
And then there&#39;s the insane and dastardly conspiracy that involves Ronald Reagan (also Showalter), who is now instigated by George W. Bush (a tried and true travesty by Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of the franchise is its retreats.
It&#39;s especially funny to see the eternally young Rudd humming Matt Dillon&#39;s song from The Loners, whose character, former big man Andy, now looks like an old man.
The success of this franchise could be occasional frenzy like the recursive series &quot;Seven Up&quot; until it gets to what, in my opinion, would be its logical conclusion: &quot;Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later&quot;, where in the last stage, the whole company would go to the cinema for the premiere of the film &quot;Hot American Summer&quot;.
&quot;Comrade Detective&quot; on Amazon appeals to a different type of nostalgia: Cold War memories from &quot;The Americans&quot;, &quot;Blast Blonde&quot; or even &quot;Shine&quot; with its imagery of the struggle between East and West.
Created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Reese Thomas, this comedy is a TV movie: an 80s Romanian police drama about two policemen in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the Marxist-Leninist way.
Florin Piersik Jr. and Corneliu Ulich play the lead roles - Gregor, who has seen life, and Joseph Gordon-Levitt, the idealistic Josef.
This is a brilliant idea.
But just an idea.
There are a few visual jokes (cops spend their time watching a chess match like Americans might watch football).
A team of acclaimed voice-overs - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - make for a fun &quot;guess the voice&quot; game.
But &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; clings to the plausibility of a clumsy propaganda drama—there&#39;s even a hitman wearing a Ronald Reagan mask—that it often looks like.
Six long episodes are drawn out, and it&#39;s not very funny and not often.
If it had been made shorter, &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; could have done a better job with its satire in the spirit of agitprop; for example, every time Gregor and Josef visit the American embassy, there are two fat people sitting in the lobby eating a bunch of hamburgers.
To the imaginary communist viewer, this image says that Western culture is capable of turning anything into a gorge.
The fictional Romanian filmmakers are not so wrong: We do this even with our own recent history, and with theirs too.
