Bank of England to keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce later that interest rates will remain unchanged after weak economic growth and waning inflation dampened rumors of a possible hike.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would remain sluggish and left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on household incomes.
The Bank&#39;s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6 to 2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer committee members in favor of a rate hike this month as weak economic growth dampened support for a hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its upside forecasts to 1.7% percent in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018, and warned that the pressure on family incomes would continue, while inflation is still expected to rise by about until 3%.
However, the bank has warned that rate hikes over the next few years will be needed to control Brexit-driven inflation, and said borrowing costs are likely to have to be raised more than expected in financial markets.
The members of the committee also voted to abandon part of the huge package of measures to develop the economy, launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close a term financing plan under which it provides cheap loans to banks, although it said it now has another £15bn to lend up to £115bn under the plan.
In the minutes of the rate decision, the bank said: &quot;According to MPC key forecasts, gross domestic product (GDP) growth remains slow in the near term, while pressure on household real incomes continues to weigh on consumption.&quot;
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that &quot;some tightening of fiscal policy&quot; would be needed to stem inflation, &quot;somewhat more&quot; than markets are expecting.
At the moment, markets are predicting the first rise in the third quarter of next year and another one in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases would be &quot;gradual&quot; and &quot;limited.&quot;
The bank&#39;s upside forecasts for this year and next are lower than those made in May, which were 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank left unchanged its forecast for 1.8% in 2018.
Following the news, the sterling fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and 0.4% to €1.11.
The decision not to change the rate was taken after the recent disappointing growth figures weakened the increased expectation of an increase; GDP then grew by 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
Growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will pick up slightly later in the year, a bank spokesman said.
The bank&#39;s latest inflation report gave households little cause for rejoicing, hit by high inflation and modest wage hikes: the bank said the pressure would increase before easing.
The bank added that fiscal policy &quot;cannot prevent&quot; a payroll blowout in the next few years, but expects wages to recover &quot;significantly&quot; by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of growing demand for British goods, thanks to the weak pound, which offsets some of the lower consumer spending.
