She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that held that the National Health Service had the ability to pay for PrEP despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed as a &quot;major innovation&quot; by NHS England President Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Office (NAT) called it a &quot;turning point&quot;.
Before the full launch of the program across England by April 2018, STDs in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start enrolling people, with more to join the program in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medications taken before sex to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When PrEP is taken before sex, there are enough certain drugs in the body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Eligible patients include gay and bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are HIV positive and are not receiving successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select eligible participants who agree to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals whose partners are not known to have their HIV status controlled by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and registered with a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest participating STI clinic.
The program will cost £10m and NHS England this week signed an agreement to provide the drug after an international tender for procurement.
The study is designed to explore the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who the drug&#39;s target audience is, its uptake, and its use on a large scale.
“This critical innovation should complement and enhance the broader and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in the fight against one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT (National AIDS Control Agency), said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted to people who need help and are at risk, has the potential to make a difference in the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV will have access to a new and empowering drug through this NHS-sponsored study in England that can be controlled by the individual without having to discuss it with a partner, leading to to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.&quot;
Ian Greene, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “Now the first priority is to ensure that the trial rolls out rapidly across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is left behind.
