Judges are offered to be protected from chairmen
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The Human Rights Council proposes to limit the powers of chairmen of courts and introduce their election.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential order.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
The Human Rights Council carried out this work on the instructions of Vladimir Putin dated January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with members of the council.
At a meeting with council members on December 8, 2016, they discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see &quot;Kommersant&quot; dated December 9).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals that relate both to the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights activists is to limit the powers of court chairmen in order to increase the independence of other judges.
If a candidate for the position of a judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judiciary, then the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, should nominate him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to distribute cases for consideration among judges.
To do this, experts admit, a specially written computer program can.
The HRC also believes that the chairman has no right &quot;to predetermine the results of a judge&#39;s qualification assessment, to initiate disciplinary action against him, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments.&quot;
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to switch to &quot;the election of court chairmen by the judges themselves&quot; and &quot;to empower them for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation.&quot;
Now all chairmen of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize appeal and cassation in courts of general jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that &quot;it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts.&quot;
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
Under them, there are &quot;judicial districts&quot; that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but due to this guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use the &quot;telephone law&quot;.
The HRC proposes to reinforce justices of the peace with people&#39;s assessors in order to consider certain &quot;categories of civil and administrative cases&quot; with their participation.
For example, about the deprivation of parental rights, about reinstatement at work, about protecting honor and dignity, about depriving a driver&#39;s license, etc.
&quot;These are just our proposals,&quot; Tamara Morshchakova, a member of the Human Rights Council and a retired judge of the Constitutional Court, explained to Kommersant.
She also recalled that the president&#39;s order applied not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
The Armed Forces (the Prosecutor General&#39;s Office and the Ombudsman for Human Rights in the Russian Federation among co-executors) still have time to fulfill the order.
Chairman of the Supreme Court Vyacheslav Lebedev must report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation by September 1.
Living the High Life: A mezzanine floor and clever design tricks transform this small Earl&#39;s Court apartment into a spacious home
Joan Lee, a retired banker with a passion for real estate renovation, moved from her spacious Knightsbridge home to an apartment in Earl&#39;s Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a pretty typical Queen Anne house, and it&#39;s in favor of the new design that Joan didn&#39;t pack up her things and move out again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area,” says Joan.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
They showed me this apartment in Earl&#39;s Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and bid the same day.&quot;
The 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation since its first viewing.
It was originally a complex one-bedroom apartment—one had to go through the kitchen to get to the bedroom—and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine floor to make the most of the generous ceiling heights.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my requirements,” she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck &amp; Shed to use 12.5-foot-high ceilings to create a home that would not only be a successful project, but fit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a mezzanine where one could stand upright.
Erfan had to think creatively to get through the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We needed to arrange the rooms in such a way that they were one above the other, and did not have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to curve the structures so that they are at the correct height and allow the use of rooms from above and below.”
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in the allotted space - and much more.
From the mezzanine, a vintage copper skylight window from Retrouvius overlooks the chic living room below.
Mirrored furniture with golden finishes, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures by Serge Mouy set the tone for the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short hallway is lined with mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored privacy panel feels like a window into another room.
At the entrance, mirrored cabinets serve to store all of Joan&#39;s crockery.
To create a feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block off the kitchen when not in use.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a door that slides up, like in a garage.
“The art of engineering was involved here,” says Erfan of the steel-reinforced wood fiber panel door.
&quot;It&#39;s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.&quot;
Through judicious use of space and storage space, Joan gained an additional 16 square meters, an extra bedroom and an improved layout.
“At the end of the day, floor space is what you will be selling, which is what your property is valued at,” says Erfan.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they have been able to increase the floor area by using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the home,” says Erfan.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It is important, but does not touch the strings of our hearts.
This is a testament to the fact that, through good design and increased footage, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can choose to stay.
