President Trump&#39;s relationship with television dates back decades - and now that he&#39;s in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
“When Trump, as a candidate, resented unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to show him that he was getting fair coverage from publications that could be persuaded,” Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico at the time that &quot;according to six former members of the campaign staff, in order to keep Trump&#39;s habit of tweeting under control, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information that came to him personally.&quot;
Fine.
But the idea that Trump&#39;s tweeting habit was ever &quot;under control&quot; is simply ridiculous.
Maybe these members of the campaign staff know something we don&#39;t, like that if it wasn&#39;t for them, Trump&#39;s tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets Trump didn&#39;t release.
If his staff had kept him out of trouble even a few times, their efforts had not been in vain.
But no one has always been able to keep Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by giving Trump material - credible or not - that confirms their views.
&quot;Politico&quot; - just in time for this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly slip questionable information to the president.
Here is one example, described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Current and former Trump employees say that Trump can react very harshly to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds who was behind them.
This happened in late February, when someone slipped the President a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles Q. Johnson, which accused Deputy Chief of Staff Cathy Welsh of being &quot;behind a series of leaks&quot; at the White House. .
It doesn&#39;t matter that Johnson is permanently banned from Twitter for violent behavior, that he didn&#39;t present specific facts, or that he launched false accusations in the past and then dropped them.
Trump read the article and started asking employees about Welsh.&quot;
Goldmacher adds that then chief of staff Reince Priebus and secretary of staff Rob Porter were &quot;trying to build a system to manage the flow of paperwork that Trump gets and document it.&quot;
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature and his aides still fight each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly&#39;s task very difficult.
Tyumen prosecutor&#39;s office fights HIV dissident
The prosecutor&#39;s office challenged the decision of the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local resident whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died due to the fact that the mother is an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from liability in connection with reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor&#39;s office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished, so as not to create a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under Part 1 of Art. 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection stage 4B.
According to the prosecutor&#39;s office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
&quot;The woman was not treated herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist,&quot; the prosecutor&#39;s office of the Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case was received by the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to close it.
The petition for this was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that &quot;he forgave his wife, he has no claims against her, she made amends for the damage and apologized.&quot;
The prosecutor&#39;s office did not agree with the court&#39;s decision and filed an appeal, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be canceled and sent for a new trial.
The girl died, and it is impossible to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection,&quot; the press service of the prosecutor&#39;s office said.
According to the oversight body, she must be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents will follow her example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care due to the refusal of their parents.
&quot;And this situation has already improved - during the year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat their children for HIV changed their minds - they allowed them to be diagnosed, they began to take drugs,&quot; said Elena Loseva, press secretary of the AIDS Center.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents by legislative means, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers are not allowed to examine them, they hide, run away with their children from hospitals.
What danger do HIV dissidents pose?
At the end of last year, sociologists from St. Petersburg presented the results of Russia&#39;s first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and they see a serious threat in their spread.
A terrible photo session that ended in tragedy took place on Thursday, August 3, at the Grechany railway station in Khmelnitsky.
A cheerful company of tipsy young people was walking along the bridge over the railway tracks, where a freight train was just standing.
One of my friends came up with the idea to take a spectacular selfie on the roof of the car, FACTS was told in the police communication sector in the Khmelnytsky region.
The guy began to descend from the bridge onto the train, but due to his indiscretion, he caught on a power line and instantly received an electric shock.
Fortunately, the dispatcher of the station became aware of this incident and immediately called an ambulance.
Before the arrival of doctors, the victim was moved to a safe place, and then hospitalized in the burn department of the Khmelnytsky Regional Clinical Hospital.
The man was diagnosed with burns of the torso of 1-2 degrees.
Doctors now assess his condition as stable.
Law enforcers remind that in recent years, extreme selfies on the roofs of high-rise buildings, bridges, and moving vehicles have become increasingly popular.
The police are urging people to be vigilant and not allow such photo shoots, especially among children and teenagers.
Scientists admit the existence of oceans on ancient Venus
Oceans may have existed on ancient Venus.
This assumption was made by French scientists.
Scientists have created a computer model that demonstrated the process of water formation on the surface of the planets, writes Science News.
It turned out that on Venus at the beginning of its history, oceans were formed, in which there was 10% more water than now on Earth.
Earlier, &quot;Arguments of the Week&quot; wrote that, according to the scientists&#39; hypothesis, an ocean could exist on Mars 4 billion years ago.
Foreign experts in the course of their research came to the conclusion that the water body was located in the northern hemisphere of the Red Planet.
Three injured in San Francisco park shooting
Three people were injured in a shooting in San Francisco, reports the Associated Press.
The incident took place in Dolores Park when there were a significant number of visitors.
According to witnesses, several men who were on the bridge began to shout threats.
One of them pulled out a weapon and started shooting at people.
The appearance of the intruders could not be seen, since they had everything but their eyes closed.
Another was provided with medical assistance, after which he was released.
The third wounded man is a minor, there are no details about his condition.
Situated on a hill, Dolores Park is a popular destination for locals and tourists.
On July 1, at least 17 people were injured in a shooting at a nightclub in Little Rock, Arkansas.
Several other visitors were injured trying to leave the premises.
rock band Louna will present a new album in Barnaul
The concert of the rock band Louna will be held in Barnaul on October 17th.
The musicians will present their new album &quot;Brave New World&quot;, which has become one of the most anticipated releases of the year.
The team is preparing a conceptual show that will become the brightest in the concert history of the group.
&quot;Brave New World&quot; is the fourth album by the Russian rock band Louna.
Its name is associated with the famous dystopian novel by O. Huxley &quot;Brave New World&quot;.
The new songs do not retell the book, but tell about a society that lives according to the law of dystopia, &quot;blindly believing in propaganda and imposed values.&quot;
The listeners helped the group to raise money for recording the album: more than 1,200 people supported the project on the Planet.ru website.
His first album &quot;Make It Louder!&quot; Louna released in 2010.
Two years later, the musicians presented the disc &quot;Time X&quot;, and in 2013 they recorded the album &quot;We are Louna&quot; (2013).
