The group consists of Lusine Gevorkyan (vocals), Vitaly Demidenko (bass guitar), Ruben Kazaryan (guitar), Sergey Ponkratiev (guitar), Leonid Kinzbursky (drums).
The concert will take place in the Barnaul club &quot;Pharaoh&quot; on October 17 at 19.00.
Ticket price: from 1200 to 2600 rubles.
Louna is one of the most sought after bands on the Russian rock scene.
The team was founded in 2008.
Their debut concert took place in 2009.
The group won several times in different categories of the &quot;Devil&#39;s Dozen&quot; hit parade.
Gypsies overcame the moat and returned to the &quot;street of millionaires&quot;
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midlands are once again at odds with determined gypsies who have crossed a municipal moat to reclaim the field next to their homes.
The gypsies parked 20 mobile homes in a field bordering Solihull&#39;s wealthy street, jokingly called &quot;millionaires&#39; street.&quot;
Bringing with them horses, babies, and many motorhomes, they returned after being kicked out no later than May, unimpeded by the ditch dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their incursions.
This tactful company found a gap in the defenses and pushed their vehicles through the area they had left unfenced to make room for a path.
Angry residents attacked the municipality of Solihull, saying that it was &quot;unable to solve this problem.&quot;
An anonymous local resident said: &quot;They arrived here on Monday evening after being driven from Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by.&quot;
The municipality should be shamed and forced to act because they are completely incapable of solving this problem.
The gypsies were here in May, they were driven away, and now they are back again.
More gypsies came last night, and perhaps more tonight.
&quot;The City of Birmingham knows how to deal with this issue, they are getting long-term court orders to protect their parks,&quot; she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road and I don&#39;t like that I keep paying Council Tax and the City can&#39;t even stop it.&quot;
One local resident, who wished to remain anonymous, said: &quot;This is ridiculous, we just saw these gypsies leave the previous time, and here you go, this scourge continues.&quot;
This time there were more of them, and we even saw a horse grazing in the meadow.”
A Solihull municipality spokesman said: “We are aware of the illegal camp on land near Streetsbrook Road and are cooperating with the Solihull police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them out as soon as possible.”
To assist us in gathering evidence, it is essential that as many local residents as possible report any anti-social or criminal behavior to the police on 101.
This allows you to get an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
Crimea joint-stock plant champagne wines &quot;New World&quot;
State Unitary Enterprise of the Republic of Crimea &quot;Plant of Champagne Wines &quot;Novy Svet&quot;&quot; was decided to corporatize, transforming it into OJSC &quot;Plant of Champagne Wines &quot;Novy Svet&quot;&quot;, follows from the order of the Minister of Property and Land Relations of Crimea Anna Anyukhina.
100% of the company&#39;s shares will remain in the state property of the Crimea.
The authorized capital of the joint-stock company will amount to 595.5 million rubles. and will consist of 5.955 million ordinary shares with a nominal value of 100 rubles. each.
The Ministry of Agriculture of the Crimea stated that if funds were not found for the modernization of the enterprise within the next three years, then there would be a threat of stopping the plant.
Depreciation of fixed assets at the enterprise is about 60-70%.
The modernization of the enterprise requires 1.2 billion rubles. Due to the peculiarities of the organizational and legal form, it is obliged to give 50% of the profit to the budget.
What remains is not enough to carry out the modernization plan.
&quot;It is problematic to get money from the owner, it is difficult to talk about raising borrowed funds from large credit organizations,&quot; Sergey Petelin, deputy head of the Crimean Ministry of Agriculture, said in April this year.
The Crimean Parliament included the enterprise in the forecast privatization plan for 2017.
It was proposed to hold it corporatization and put up for auction.
An Interfax source in the Crimean authorities estimated the possible cost of selling the enterprise at $40 million, and the investor&#39;s investment in modernization at another $30 million.
&quot;New World&quot; in 2016 increased the production of sparkling wines by 2.8% compared to the level of 2015 - up to 1.52 million bottles.
In 2017, Novy Svet intended to produce 1.6 million bottles.
The company was founded in 1878 by Prince Lev Golitsyn as a factory for the production of sparkling wine in the Novy Svet estate he acquired.
The plant is located on 11 hectares of land.
Nizhny Novgorod third-graders destroyed more than 40 tombstones
Employees of the Main Directorate of the Ministry of Internal Affairs for the Nizhny Novgorod Region identified the citizens who destroyed 46 tombstones in the cemetery of the city of Lyskovo.
The perpetrators were third grade students.
The first statement that the tombstones were damaged by unknown people was received by the Russian MIA for the Lyskovsky district on June 27.
In total, 24 people turned to the police about this.
As a result, a criminal case was initiated under article 244 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation &quot;Destruction, damage or desecration of burial places.&quot;
As a result of the investigation, the police identified the suspects, they turned out to be two schoolchildren aged 8 and 9 years.
The juvenile delinquents told the police that they were interested to see how the monuments fell, and this prompted them to hooligan actions.
Preventive measures were taken with children and their parents.
Italy is hardening its tone towards NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue boats in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
&quot;If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,&quot; Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin daily Stampa.
Minniti&#39;s warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually collaborating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has worked for only a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
“For us, saving human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone now,” the organization said in a social media statement.
&quot;We will be able to evaluate all the allegations made now only after we collect all the information and can assess the situation.&quot;
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Jugend Rettet&#39;s Juventa since October.
Its crew is suspected of taking on board full lifeboats migrants sent directly to them by traffickers and allowing the smugglers to leave with the boats they could reuse.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to prosecution materials published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the instructions of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the area, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The code of conduct stipulates mainly that the Juventa-type vessels will have on board an Italian police officer who will supervise their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to abide by the code: Save the Children, Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considers the new rules unnecessary but acceptable, provided they do not entail any &quot;significant change or interference&quot; with its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign was the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
&quot;In recent days, we have begun to see light at the end of the tunnel,&quot; the minister said.
He announced plans for further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
&quot;In Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict&quot;
The authorities of the Russian Federation have recently noticeably stepped up their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations from the opposing Libyan sides have made frequent visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group for intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic, Lev Dengov, told Kommersant what goals Moscow is pursuing in this region and on whom it is relying.
Almost nothing is known about the Contact Group on Libya, which you chair.
Here, for example, is the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is a veil of secrecy.
What exactly are you doing, what are your goals?
The contact group was created on the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (a Duma deputy from Chechnya. - Kommersant).
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention of the Russian tanker &quot;Mechanic Chebotarev&quot; in Libya (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - Kommersant).
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group was created from military experts, representatives of the State Duma, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it happen that you led it?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I was approached to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the &quot;Mechanic Chebotarev&quot;.
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all major groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Sarraj is based. - Kommersant) and Tobruk (the seat of the parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. - Kommersant).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Deputy Prime Minister of Libya - &quot;Kommersant&quot;), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize in particular: in Libya, we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are in dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
Currently, the contact group includes five people.
Among them are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to introduce representatives of the Institute of the Near East of the Russian Academy of Sciences into the group of experts on the region.
None of our employees are permanently in Libya, there is no need for this yet.
Are there Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on which side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is required.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or such cities, closed to a certain point for us, like Misurata (where the militia units are based, which played a role in the overthrow of the Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and noticeably intensified in subsequent years. - Kommersant).
We arrived in Misurata in January of this year.
They frightened us, they said that everyone there is entirely Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the role of the Islamists there in reality.
In Misurata, we met with all representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of IS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the Islamic State banned in Russia - Kommersant).
We wanted to look at them, get to know these people, verify the information that it was they who played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits to himself.
And what conclusion did you come to?
&quot;Islamic state&quot; in Libya won not Haftar?
This was not what he did.
Haftar conducted operations on the other front, in Benghazi.
And IS in Sirte was fought by structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And by the way, we invited the people who carried out this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from April 19 to April 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the National Guard.
You, as we understand, visit all Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of the local elites and warlords.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the agreements on a ceasefire, on holding elections, which Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarraj reached in Paris at the end of July?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, agreements will be broken, hostilities will resume, the parties will try to single-handedly seize power?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders spoke extremely negatively about each other.
As for Russia&#39;s position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many people believe in it.
We encountered this situation when we were in Misurata, and on that very day Haftar boarded the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurata they did not believe in a coincidence.
We were told: &quot;You are probably very brave people who came to us today.&quot;
But our task is precisely to show that we do not support only Haftar, we are in dialogue with all the key participants in the conflict in Libya.
You spoke with Haftar.
Does the fact that he studied in the USSR twice make it easier to understand with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, it is very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And by the way, not only with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or back in the Soviet Union.
And now they speak excellent Russian.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgia for it.
Do you think it is likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will soon be lifted?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have already said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be roughly on equal footing.
As for the arms embargo, the Libyans are constantly calling for Russia to somehow contribute to its lifting.
Now in Libya, the process of drafting a constitution is actively moving forward.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and reach an internal consensus.
Then elections should be held, which was also discussed at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections take place and a legitimate government is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such a status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned to its fate by its allies from the EU.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its connections with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the option that Haftar&#39;s troops will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers who smuggle immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia&#39;s support, because Moscow is conducting a dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata and the south of the country at the same time.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Are we talking about southerners stopping the flow of migrants at distant approaches?
That is, relatively speaking, they turned back the buses in which Nigerian migrants travel?
We are striving for this.
But it&#39;s not easy.
Some clans and groups have an interest in keeping these flows going.
We hope to contribute to uniting the southerners in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see a unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical are his views?
Will this become an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about it.
In my opinion, on the contrary, he is an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself adheres to the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where did he get such a reputation from?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial branches are located.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
And we mixed all the cards for them and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has entered into a cooperation agreement with Libya&#39;s state oil company, NOC.
NOC director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Igor Sechin, the head of Rosneft, made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess resell.
And what other economic interests does Russia have in Libya?
The plans to re-sign the contracts concluded under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
And the Libyans have something to pay?
Well, they have oil.
So, just like in the case with Iran, we are talking about the &quot;oil in exchange for services&quot; scheme?
I don’t know what the scheme will be, I don’t deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are there, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans come to an agreement among themselves so that they can establish order in themselves and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is precisely the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze the terrorists out of there.
Do you have information about the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that today there is not a single native of Russia and other countries of the former USSR there.
He said that he had about 50,000 telephone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - Kommersant) and Russian was not heard there.
And from which states then are these militants?
I would not like to go into these details.
Let&#39;s formulate the question differently then.
How many Libyans themselves are among the Islamist militants in Libya?
There are practically no Libyans among them, they are no more than 5%.
The rest are strangers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks following the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
It&#39;s hard to say now.
There are still several visits to take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the talks.
In the Chekhov Museum, benefactors raised money for an expensive gift for a sick boy
In the Melikhovo Museum-Reserve near Moscow, a nine-year-old boy Sasha Matsola, who has cerebral palsy, cerebral hydrocephalus and complete blindness, will receive a specialized treadmill as a gift on August 5.
A useful present will be presented to Sasha by Oksana Kosareva, Minister of Culture of the Moscow Region, and Konstantin Bobkov, Director of the Museum.
The money for the simulator was collected during the charity marathon &quot;Don&#39;t Get Tired of Doing Good&quot;, which took place in Melikhovo on July 15 on Chekhov&#39;s Memorial Day.
On the eve of the marathon, the museum received a letter from Sasha, who lives in the village of Manushkino, Chekhov District, a letter: &quot;My eyes can&#39;t see at all, so I asked my mother to write this letter.&quot;
&quot;I would really like to receive a treadmill as a gift so that my legs become strong and I would learn to walk a little.&quot;
And Sasha&#39;s dream came true!
After the presentation, the Museum-Reserve will host a &quot;Concert-postscript&quot; - the famous pianist, Honored Artist of Russia Alexander Gindin will perform a potpourri of popular classical works.
During the charity marathon in Melikhovo, the choir of the Voznesenskaya Davydova Hermitage, the ringers of the workshop of Ilya Drozdikhin, students of the Moscow Conservatory named after P.I. Tchaikovsky and the Gnessin Russian Academy, artists of the Melikhovsky Theater &quot;Chekhov Studio&quot;.
Auctions were held for visitors, a book fair and a charity sale of souvenirs with the marathon logo were organized.
The Melikhovo Museum-Reserve took the initiative to make Chekhov&#39;s Memorial Day on July 15 a single day of charity in all museums of the Moscow region.
A 30-year-old resident of Olevsk, Zhytomyr region, near the local football stadium, fired several shots at the teenagers who were there.
According to the suspect, he was angered by the noise, FACTS was told in the communication department of the police of the Zhytomyr region.
After that, the man went to a cafe located nearby.
He had a conflict in the building, during which the man used a device for firing rubber bullets, injuring one of the visitors.
The 34-year-old victim received the necessary medical assistance, there is no threat to his life.
Police and paramedics arrived at the scene, but the shooter had fled by then.
