The murder of a journalist highlights the growing danger in Mexico.
The staff of the weekly newspaper Ryodose usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crime in the state of Sinaloa, linked to organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing drug war.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about safety.
They were told that they should change their habits.
The two senior journalists discussed whether it seemed safer to take the children with them to the office, which had already been hit by a grenade in 2009, or to leave them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on a blackboard hanging in the room: enemies, neutrals, allies.
They asked the journalists to give names for each column - no evidence needed, suspicions and inner feelings would be enough.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being on the payroll of the government or the cartels, a whole list of scoundrels, because of which the work of covering the chaos in Mexico becomes dangerous.
The violence does not give respite, and among the corpses that multiply in the country, more and more journalists: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people after attacks and threats are under federal protection; and this year, at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, Riodose co-founder Javier Valdes Cardenas.
&quot;The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,&quot; Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violent drug crime.
His absence is felt very acutely, although his presence is everywhere - a large photo of Valdez showing the middle finger, with the inscription &quot;Justice&quot; hanging on the facade of the Ryodose building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ybarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that feature his smile, his bespectacled face, or his signature panama hat.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their shared trauma, their nightmares, their insomnia, their paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor&#39;s office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As is the case with most of the thousands of drug- and organized-crime-related murders committed each year, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Ryodose journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although the surroundings are now much more dangerous.
Without information about the killers, without justice, talking about security at meetings is of little use, says Ibarra.
&quot;It&#39;s very stupid to waste time in this seminar,&quot; he says.
&quot;Until we know the cause, we suspect everyone.&quot;
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodose office in Culiacan, the state capital.
He only managed a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was pulled over by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper - which means &quot;Twelfth River&quot;.
The shooter drove off in his car and wrecked it nearby.
Valdes was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually spread quickly around Culiacan.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdez.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the US last January, Sinaloa has become one of the country&#39;s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions fight to fill the vacuum.
Let&#39;s not talk about the fact that one or more people are killed on the streets of Sinaloa every day, or that the cemetery is filled with the ornate two-story mausoleums of drug kings, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let&#39;s forget for a moment that a state of &quot;calm&quot; is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a seaside state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this, and despite the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his job, Ismail Bojorquez, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Ryodose, is crushed by guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso López, the leader of one of the cartel&#39;s rival factions that is at war with the sons of Guzmán.
The publication might have angered the sons; people believed to be members of the gang bought up all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the newsstands.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that was reporting the same story was seized.
Valdes was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroesta and in 2003, along with five colleagues, founded Riodose by selling his $50 shares.
In Sinaloa, &quot;it was impossible to do journalism without talking about drugs,&quot; Bojorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for being bold and honest, and sales and advertising revenue grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this publication they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Ryodose received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating Mexico&#39;s drug trade, wherever it may lead.
He frankly admitted that he was scared.
&quot;I want to move on with my life,&quot; he said at the CPJ awards.
Drug dealing in Sinaloa &quot;is a way of life,&quot; he told Rompeviento TV last October.
&quot;You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either that or you&#39;re just fooling around.&quot;
I don&#39;t want to be asked, &quot;What were you doing when there were so many deaths around...why didn&#39;t you tell me what was going on?&quot;
The Riodose staff miss Valdes, the prankster who swore like a porter, a friend generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to keep alive.
They relied on their established order.
He had to always wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and always sit at the same table there.
Now they ask: was it his love for a once-in-a-lifetime routine that ruined him?
His death made them question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
&quot;They don&#39;t like it when you look into their wives, their children, their legal businesses, and their illegal drug airfields.
&quot;Those things were off the charts,&quot; Bojorquez said.
The result, even at the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from things that smell bad.
The problem, says Riodose editor Andrés Villareal, is that &quot;the sense of smell can be tricked...and then what happened to Javier happens.&quot;
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states where there is a poisonous mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
Cell phones were suddenly banned from entering the room where Riodose employees had gathered for security training, days before it became known that spyware, which is sold exclusively to governments, is being used in Mexico to spy on journalists and social activists.
Outside, two policemen take shelter in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were tasked by the state government to guard the Ryodose office, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these police officers were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officers about whom the governor himself said that they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists traveled to the mountainous area, which is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue of &quot;Riodose&quot; counted on three main themes.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor&#39;s hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping in one of Culiacan&#39;s most expensive restaurants, a block from the prosecutor&#39;s office.
It has not been officially announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so care had to be taken when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was the favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and the authorities.
One of the journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of government for almost the past century.
Recently, high-profile allegations of corruption have been leveled against several PRI governors.
Villareal asked journalists to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including one when &quot;El Chapo&quot; Guzmán&#39;s son eluded a military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have been looking for Valdez&#39;s column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
&quot;Earlier we would have known what happened,&quot; says Villarreal, 46, nicknamed &quot;El Flaco&quot; for his lean physique.
&quot;Today all channels of communication with our sources have been severed.&quot;
Valdez&#39;s office is now being used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killings of journalists, because the staff have become what they never thought they would be: press activists.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took some posters and went the next morning to a demonstration outside the local prosecutor&#39;s office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacán in the west of the country three days after Valdes was killed.
A burnt body was found and authorities said it was him based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak out louder, organize protests and write &quot;SOS Press&quot; on sidewalks and walls.
Director Bojorquez was in Washington that day, trying to garner international support for justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez&#39;s assassination, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their assassinations for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to be given more assignments to cover the activities of the government, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdez has said many times that journalists in Mexico are &quot;surrounded&quot; by organized crime, its accomplices in the government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that it&#39;s not just drug gangs that kill reporters; they do so at the behest of politicians and security forces in collusion with organized crime.
The press protection committee Articulo 19 believes that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
&quot;In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,&quot; Ramirez says.
Of course, killings intimidate people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body, believed to be from the Zetas cartel: &quot;I&#39;m here for my articles.&quot;
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some publications chose to close down, like El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslava Brich was killed in March.
Others continue to hang on, like &quot;El Mañana&quot; from Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed the drug cartels with a front-page editorial titled &quot;What do you want from us?&quot;
Some journalists have left their home states or even the country.
It&#39;s a painful decision.
It&#39;s hard to find work in exile, and they&#39;re still on the lookout for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently was the case with photographer Rubén Espinoza, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work balance risky decisions daily.
Ybarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits he&#39;s terrified of writing about the drug trade.
&quot;Mexico is going to hell and that&#39;s why I became a journalist,&quot; he says.
Last Friday at midnight, when the last issue was ready for print, the publishers of Ryodose were sitting on the sidewalk outside the office drinking beer when all of a sudden their phones rang at the same time.
A series of shootings between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlán left behind a confirmed 19 dead.
The war continued to escalate, as promised in a series of messages from the cartels found in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news on the Ryodose website via their mobile phones.
The first page had to be redone the next day.
Sirens wailed nearby, another firefight in the vicinity.
The Bohorques looked to see if the police guarding them were ready for defense.
If they were scared, they didn&#39;t show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was exposed to all of Sinaloa, the Ryodose staff continued his work.
&quot;How can you think about shutting down,&quot; said Bojorquez, &quot;if on the very day that Javier was killed, an intern asked me to send her outside to report?&quot;
Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it seems like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
The first found remains of the incredible rhinoceros-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner are so well-preserved that experts have dubbed it the &quot;Mona Lisa of dinosaurs,&quot; researchers say.
It was so well-preserved that they were even able to determine that its scaly skin color was reddish-brown - and to say that it had, in some ways, a &quot;dark past.&quot;
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as &quot;the best-preserved Thyreophora ever found and one of the finest dinosaur specimens in the world.&quot;
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaurus that lived during the mid-Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredible good condition has stunned researchers, who call it &quot;really remarkable.&quot;
This herbivorous thyreophore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind ever found, according to articles in National Geographic magazine.
It was found by Sean Funk while working at the Suncore Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed to be different from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was underway to find the animal inside a 2,500-foot (1,100 kilogram) block of earth.
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be shown.
&quot;You just squint a little and you can almost believe it&#39;s asleep,&quot; said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology, where the creature is on display.
&quot;It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.&quot;
By examining its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite being armored and resembling a walking tank, appeared to be in considerable danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerfully armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and employed a defensive technique known as camouflage coloration, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to blend in more quickly and avoid enemies, experts say, suggesting it was preyed upon by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old nodosaur creature was widely publicized in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and have given it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli, after museum lab assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the team members who spent more than 7,000 hours on its painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and armor plates on his body.
They found camouflage coloration, a common method of defense in the animal kingdom, meaning that the creature&#39;s top was darker than its underside.
While camouflage coloration is well-established, the discovery came as a surprise because the Borealopelta dinosaur is much larger than living camouflage animals.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred camouflage to confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with camouflage coloration—such as deer, zebras, or armadillos—are much smaller and more accessible prey, suggesting that nodosaurus had to struggle to survive.
&quot;The massive predatory threat to the massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous the carnivorous dinosaurs of the Cretaceous were,&quot; Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in dinosaur scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was swept out to sea, where it sank and lay back down on the ocean floor.
In those days, Alberta was as warm as southern Florida is now, and the rivers and oceans likely extended much further inland than they do now.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, retaining the original shape of the animal,” Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous.
You don&#39;t have to use your imagination much to recreate it, you just have to squint a little and you can almost believe that he is sleeping.
The Cretaceous Period is an era when giant theropods, bipedal carnivorous dinosaurs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, the Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, one of its formidable ancestors may have hunted the thyreophora.
They include the Acrocanthosaurus, a monster 38 feet (11.5 meters) long and weighing six tons.
The scientists, whose latest discoveries are being published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was swept out to sea after death and mummified in mud.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
According to museum staff, it is the best-preserved thyreophore in the world, complete with skin and shell, and is intact from muzzle to thighbones.
On average, these creatures were about 18 feet (five meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from their shoulders.
Researchers believe this herbivorous thyreophore was plodding heavily through what is now Canada until a flooded river swept it out to sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell to the smallest detail.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well-preserved that remnants of the skin still cover the bumpy carapace plates along the dinosaur&#39;s skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, this degree of preservation is &quot;as rare as winning the lottery.&quot;
The longer I look at it, the more amazing it seems.
The fossilized remnants of the skin still cover the bumpy armored plates that dot the animal&#39;s skull.
His right front leg is extended along the side, five fingers on it are turned up.
I can count the scales on his sole.&quot;
