How one activist learned the answer to the question “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the core.
Barely a day after arriving in New York on a tourist trip, the St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an Airbnb apartment, scrolling through her Facebook feed on her phone.
She came across the post of someone from high school.
It said: &quot;The police have just killed an eighteen-year-old child, and he is still lying in the middle of the street.&quot;
Noticing that no one else in her feed had posted this information, puzzled, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
In her feed, there were many reposts by a user with the nickname @TheePharoah.
The Greater St. Louis rapper tweeted real-time coverage of the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photograph of Brown&#39;s lifeless body, sprawled across the street, where it would lie for four hours.
This is crazy, Ferrel thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put her phone down and later in the evening returned to tweeting that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of signal tape and people screaming and a man claiming to be Brown&#39;s father holding a sign that said, &quot;A Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!&quot;
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another police officer, she said, cocked his rifle and yelled, &quot;I&#39;m going to kill you all... animals!&quot;
“This is not a standard situation,” according to her own recollections, Ferrel said then.
“This is not a murder that we are used to and which we can call typical.
At that moment, I felt chills.
I got angry and cried.&quot;
She took a return ticket and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11pm, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father&#39;s house and decided that they would both leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next almost three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
It is a tale of survival and rebellion, love and loss, strength and resilience from the point of view of the people who live in the community and fill the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a floral dress and matching wreath, they reminisced about the conversation they&#39;d had countless times before that morning &quot;about the black experience and their condition.&quot;
She recalls saying, “Remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We&#39;re on our way to Ferguson now because a police officer killed an eighteen-year-old boy and it wasn&#39;t right.&quot;
&quot;I couldn&#39;t help but take it,&quot; Ferrell later said.
“What is happening today is the culmination of ... what happened before.
She should know about it, see it and be brought up on it.
She must not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of experience of black people and their situation and what we must do to become free, to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment where she herself does not personally experience obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would be doing her a disservice if I shielded her from this.”
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop on South Florissant Road, a site across the street from the police station that became a sort of campground while activists waited for reports of Officer Darren Wilson&#39;s eventual non-indictment.
There, Ferrell and her daughter joined a local entrepreneur who prepared lunch bags.
They collected packages and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little, a new type of activism took shape in Ferrell&#39;s mind.
“My activism completely changed after August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. .
“I had no experience as an organizer.
It just came.&quot;
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrel met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said that she and her chief cameraman, Lucas Alvarado-Ferrar, &quot;just wanted to document&quot; the events.
Ferrel came up with a question: &quot;Are you looking to document, or are you trying to find a story to play with?&quot;
This skepticism was inspired by numerous people, often whites, who came to the community to capitalize on its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, &quot;We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson weren&#39;t getting into the limelight, and we wanted to do it differently.&quot;
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his death row activism.
His participation evoked sympathy for the project among Ferrel and six other local residents with whom the project team Whose Streets? kept in touch during the years since Brown&#39;s assassination.
“In this documentary, no one is speaking for us or to us, it is we who are speaking,” said Davis.
&quot;That was the most important thing for me, how these people would be presented, because that&#39;s how I would be presented myself.&quot;
While the project&#39;s intent was not to focus on Ferrel&#39;s experience at all - in an effort to show that the movement &quot;isn&#39;t about a savior leader, it&#39;s about bringing the community together,&quot; Folayan said - she was the most open of the film&#39;s participants.
As a result, in &quot;Whose streets?&quot; shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrel&#39;s life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrel said, laughing about the first time she saw the finished product.
“But I understood that when you do this kind of work and humanize black people, there must be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell&#39;s story again discusses and highlights the role of the black gay woman within the larger context of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement — those who created the #BlackLivesMatter social media tag after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 — identify themselves as gay.
“Black gay women in leadership positions support this whole movement,” says Ferrel. “That’s because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black homosexual women have to bear all this burden.”
Folayan agreed with this statement, noting that &quot;the movement is, in fact, supported by black women and a lot of homosexual black women.&quot;
However, she insists that &quot;this is not a case of affirmative action&quot; and that Ferrell was not chosen as the film&#39;s central character due to her distinctive features.
&quot;She was the person who evoked that energy,&quot; she said.
“On the other hand, it’s not a coincidence that she was in the forefront, because when”
You can feel her energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, Ferguson is long gone from movie cameras, but complex racial ties remain between the community and the police.
Ferrell will be on probation for another two and a half years for blocking a highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place she calls home simply: &quot;A mess.&quot;
She&#39;s still holding on to the slogan she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson a full three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We must win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.&quot;
