The emergence of similarity: the artist creates portraits with the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the room at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people&#39;s faces hang from the ceiling on a wire - white, black and brown, all subtly similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clippings from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where the former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous WikiLeaks transmission of confidential diplomatic cables.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called &quot;The Emergence of Similarities.&quot;
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and prominent dissident whose sentence was commuted by Barack Obama just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning with a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that people with such a genome could have, Dewey-Harborg created a profound, albeit difficult to understand, manifesto about not only the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, but also the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has been open about identifying as a woman since adolescence, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 counts, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Photos of her in prison were not available, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie of Manning, in a platinum-hued wig, clearly uncomfortable driving a car; it was with this photograph that she became associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg completed her 2012 project Visions of Strangers with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, isolating DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
&quot;They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted a portrait to illustrate the article,&quot; Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new press exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited or photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she would like a portrait created from her DNA.
In an unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became pen pals and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, Repressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the President would tame Chelsea&#39;s punishment so that Chelsea could visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama actually decided to release Manning just days after the book was published came as a pleasant surprise after seven difficult years in a Kansas military prison.
There&#39;s something deep and powerful about the fact that the exhibition is opening right now, as Donald Trump is declaring war on people who give away classified information in the government and devising new ways to stir up the animosity on Twitter that he&#39;s supposed to moderate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that &quot;nothing happens by chance.&quot;
In the artist&#39;s statement written on the gallery wall, Manning&#39;s huge caption at the bottom (with a heart instead of the dot over the &quot;i&quot; in her last name) calls for an end to &quot;automatic segregation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.&quot;
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of penciled C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist sophistically puts it), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we all are, at least in our biological structure.
&quot;I hope to explain to people that our genome does not define what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is,&quot; said Dewey-Harborg; her 2007 video work &quot;False Memories&quot; is also featured here.
&quot;DNA data can tell us so many different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.&quot;
The last part of the exposition, which fit into one room, is the novel in comics mentioned above.
It shows Manning, in the style of King Kong, appearing above the US Penitentiary Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
&quot;If they kill your speech, they will win,&quot; it says.
&quot;So never shut up.&quot;
&quot;This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,&quot; says the artist, greeting us from Philadelphia.
&quot;I still get goosebumps when I talk about it.&quot;
Manning has not yet seen the exhibit in person - as the comics have presciently portrayed - but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done on purpose, like everything else in the exhibition, up to the height (5&quot;2, Manning&#39;s height), on which the genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
&quot;I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,&quot; Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
&quot;I wanted them to be like the grassroots movement that formed around Chelsea, the movement that was behind her liberation as well.&quot;
