Startups That Can Help Your Company Stop Being Another Uber
Aimee Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction at her e-commerce startup, but the surveys didn&#39;t work.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
&quot;He was never consistent and objective,&quot; said Errett, who runs Madison Reed, a 75-person San Francisco-based hair care e-commerce company.
So she turned to third parties for help.
There is now a new breed of HR startups that are helping companies figure out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to conduct rapid surveys, reach out to specific teams and demographics, offer anonymity and complaint hotlines to employees, and in some cases, allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact directly to the directorate.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics software is used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she gained a greater understanding of how her employees think and feel in her three years of using Glint.
In addition to quick surveys and questionnaires for specific teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and visualizes which departments have the most complaints and which managers have low approval ratings, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control the workplace environment or they will become another Uber caught up in a scandal when a former employee published a blog post describing a violent environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished .
For startups like Glint, this desire to be in control is a profitable business opportunity.
The fintech portal Let&#39;s Talk Pay estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw a slight uptick in interest and activity earlier this year as Uber&#39;s reputation plummeted.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has appeared among the customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom employee opinion polls, collect sensitive real-time responses, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous text message hotline that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if a top manager is affected, complaints go straight to the management.
&quot;The Court of Public Opinion has taken over from the inspectors,&quot; said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If a company is found to mistreat employees or behave unethically, even if inspectors don&#39;t intervene, the company could face costly repercussions in the form of customer boycotts, employee churn and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to make sure employees are up to date with policies and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company&#39;s headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look up the phone number or email address of the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope it was taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of legal for Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay - can be more quickly identified and addressed.
&quot;I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employee situation,&quot; said Vitrano, who leads the Ruby Tuesday network&#39;s risk management team.
“And we protect our shareholders from employee litigation.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values, and employee engagement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen&#39;s accounting firm collapsed due to ethical violations in the Enron case.
But it wasn&#39;t until &quot;social media went mainstream&quot; that companies realized they couldn&#39;t keep their dirty laundry from going viral online.
“Before they started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and opportunity that has received the backing of venture capitalists who have backed both startups.
In February, Convertent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company&#39;s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company&#39;s total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today&#39;s employees expect more from their jobs than ever before.
In highly competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and exciting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated, and that they are dedicating their time to the company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work for a company, feel they are being heard and that the work they are doing is paying off, they are more willing to make that company successful,” said Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Satisfaction at the company. &quot;LinkedIn&quot; where both &quot;Convercent&quot; and &quot;Glint&quot; are used.
Investors receive income when the companies in their portfolio are doing well; Companies do well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it&#39;s no wonder they&#39;re finding support.
Workplace culture experts say it&#39;s important to have employee engagement data.
But the data is useless until the company&#39;s trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn&#39;t come quickly enough, or not at all, frustration can set in and employees lose interest.
“If you&#39;re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
