Create a Comic Novel: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, the tiny Scotney Castle was featured in the &quot;Squeeze&quot; music video, and in the 70s and 80s served as a haunt for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy spot in the Beulah Valley of Kent, he has watched the turbulent history around him, and now he has inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a mop of hair and a penchant for historical documents, to a comic book novel.
&quot;I think it&#39;s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,&quot; he says enthusiastically.
&quot;You feel so personal when you hold this letter in your hand.&quot;
&quot;Castle in England&quot; covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about the families who lived in Scotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony Mae Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes&#39; first book to be based on archival evidence: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man&#39;s Teeth and Other Stories, a collection based on British Library documents; this project unexpectedly touched him to the core.
&quot;I could have been touched by just the fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a Jacobite double agent,&quot; he says.
&quot;It&#39;s his fingerprint&quot;
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those days a fire was lit for illumination.
And after 300 years, in the future, it seems to you that you are there too.
Oh, how I love archives!
For someone so obsessed with old papers, getting support from the National Trust and the English Council of Arts and living in a castle for four months (&quot;Honestly, I spent a little time there&quot;) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the &quot;new&quot; Victorian castle, walking through the archives and examining the estate&#39;s many treasures and antiques - for example, hyena heads on the walls or bottles that had lain in the moat for centuries.
He walked through the park and through the ruins of the old castle, talking with the foresters, gardeners and sometimes with the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
Then at night he &quot;drank whiskey and sat down to write.&quot;
The history of Scotney Castle is not well understood because the National Trust only gained full access to it in 2006 when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were just beginning to sort through the archive, which he describes as &quot;what the aristocrats have dumped in the attic for centuries.&quot;
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think land disputes are boring,” says Rhodes, “but two families fought over this birch tree.
It happens, guys!&quot;
In some of the stories in the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for a wider exploration of English history: for example, in &quot;The Worker&quot;, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants&#39; Revolution of 1381.
&quot;There is a riot that took place at the castle in 1380 in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex,&quot; says Rhodes.
&quot;A peasant uprising has started in these parts, and I thought a riot would be a good start.
Maybe they were related?
Other plots are strongly connected to the history of the castle - for example, &quot;The Priest&quot;, which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Durrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Durrell, who is believed to have faked his own funeral by stuffing the coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrels are the favorite Rhodes family of all that inhabited the Scotneys: &quot;The gentlemen seem to have been complete crooks, forever getting into debt and spending money on things they could not afford.
Through the generations, male Durrells have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women - I imagine them as a bunch of pretty guys who know how to look after heiresses of great fortunes.
After finishing work at the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to get a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamänmäki, a place where there was a sanatorium at the beginning of the 20th century, and then it was again overgrown with forest.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
&quot;I was sad to leave,&quot; he says.
&quot;I felt something like this: damn it, I have to return to real life again.&quot;
