Andrei Okhlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known to Kommersant, Andrey Okhlopkov, technical director of the Vostochny cosmodrome, began work at the Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (GKNPTs).
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Vostochny cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the leadership of the Center for the Operation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (TsENKI), he was transferred to an enterprise in Moscow Fili, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Okhlopkov will not have a substitute: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and the functionality will be scattered over the divisions of TsENKI.
The fact that the technical director of Vostochny and deputy general director of TsENKI for technological development, Andrey Okhlopkov, went to work at the Khrunichev State Research and Production Space Center, Kommersant was told by top managers of several space industry enterprises, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
&quot;He has been working in a new post for several weeks,&quot; Kommersant&#39;s interlocutors in the industry clarified.
It was not possible to get an operational comment from TsENKI on Thursday, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself was unavailable for comment.
However, Kommersant&#39;s information was officially confirmed by the GKNPTs.
He made a decision to move to the position of director for coordination of production, the company said. - Andrey Okhlopkov has fully fulfilled the task assigned to him to ensure the launch minimum for the first launch at the Vostochny cosmodrome.
Mr. Okhlopkov moved to work at TsENKI in 2013, having served in the space forces, in particular at Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the &quot;northern&quot; cosmodrome, he served as first deputy commander with the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, at his suggestion, regional businessmen received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean up the detachable parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The responsibilities for technological development assigned to him at TsENKI extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of a cosmodrome in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, then head of the Federal Space Agency, said in an interview with Kommersant that the state of affairs on Vostochny &quot;was critical as early as October 2013.&quot;
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made during planning: the completion of construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were scheduled for the same time - the end of 2015.
In order to launch before the end of the year, it was decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the deadlines were shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, I had to go for a trick: TsENKI specialists began to conduct parallel installation of process equipment at unfinished facilities.
Andrey Okhlopkov was the main supporter of this idea.
Despite the risks that existed and the postponement that happened (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz flew away only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, says a Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: “Otherwise we would not have implemented any one launch from Vostochny, but they would be engaged in construction.&quot;
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrey Okhlopkov his &quot;space Susanin&quot;, but it was from him that he almost always asked for information about the progress of construction.
Mr. Okhlopkov was also remembered for his frankness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed depriving the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the sole contractor for Vostochny and working directly with subcontractors: &quot;Why should we put all our eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?&quot;
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, TsENKI has assumed the duties of a general contractor in order to complete construction and installation work at the launch and technical complex by the launches scheduled for the fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant, the reason for Mr. Okhlopkov&#39;s transfer to a new place of work was disagreements with the leadership of TsENKI regarding how to complete the construction of structures and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontractors.
&quot;It was decided that it would be better for everyone,&quot; says one of the top managers involved in the construction of Vostochny.
An employee of the government apparatus, in turn, calls the decision strange: &quot;He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find an equivalent replacement for him.&quot;
According to Kommersant&#39;s information, this will not be required: the post of technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered among the subdivisions of TsENKI.
