Red meat, dairy, and chocolate may help relieve IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered to be a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers from the University of Washington found that the protein&#39;s main amino acid, tryptophan, promotes the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the gut ensure that harmful microbes from food do not enter the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too far off in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a particular bacterium in their gut develop tolerance-enhancing cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of protein - to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: &quot;We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.&quot;
He suggested that the same would work in humans: Combining L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, while another group, which belonged to the same strain but were kept separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the mice&#39;s gut microbiomes - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
DNA from mouse intestinal cells was sequenced and six species of bacteria were found, present in mice with immune cells but absent in mice without them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cell received L. reuteri and developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid - free of bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice&#39;s diet, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan level was halved, the number of cells also dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells that mice do, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri promote cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She says: “Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, since inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population.&quot;
