Disabled Anton Mamaev was fined
The Moscow City Court mitigated the punishment of wheelchair disabled Anton Mamaev from four and a half years in prison to a fine of 200 thousand rubles.
Earlier, by decision of the Timiryazevsky court, the convict was released from the pre-trial detention center.
At the same time, the Moscow City Court confirmed that the accused is a criminal, since he organized the robbery and theft of a scooter from a former special forces soldier.
The Moscow City Court, by its decision, reduced the punishment for Anton Mamaev to 200 thousand rubles. fine.
&quot;Mamaev is the organizer of the robbery, which also constitutes a crime, and, accordingly, such a person should be held criminally liable,&quot; Ulyana Solopova, spokeswoman for the Moscow City Court, explained to Kommersant.
In this case, the court took into account Mamaev&#39;s state of health, the actual circumstances of the case, and the absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied Art. 64 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation, according to which it is possible to impose a punishment below the lower limit.
As for Mamaev&#39;s assistant Vasily Seroshtanov, the court did not establish circumstances that would have become the basis for changing the category of gravity of the deed and changing the sentence.
Anton Mamaev himself said that he was dissatisfied with the decision of the Moscow City Court.
I am disappointed with the court&#39;s decision.
The only legal solution would be an acquittal, intends to continue to fight for justice.
His lawyer Andrei Orlov did not rule out an appeal against the verdict in the cassation instance of the Moscow City Court and the Supreme Court.
&quot;We will use all levers up to the European Court of Human Rights,&quot; he told RIA Novosti.
Recall that 28-year-old Muscovite Anton Mamaev, who suffers from spinal muscular atrophy, became a defendant in a criminal case last fall.
The disabled person claims that he bought a scooter from friends for 160 thousand rubles, in order to sell it later.
However, the owners of the motor scooter, including a former special forces fighter, said that the disabled person and his assistant Vasily Seroshtanov took away their property, threatening to use violence.
On June 30, the Timiryazevsky District Court of Moscow sentenced Vasily Seroshtanov to three years in prison, and Anton Mamaev to four and a half years in prison to be served in a penal colony (under part 2 of article 162 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
After the immobilized disabled person was placed in a pre-trial detention center, the Public Chamber, the Prosecutor General&#39;s Office, and the Commissioner for Human Rights under the President Tatyana Moskalkova joined the case.
As a result, in mid-July, Anton Mamaev was released from the pre-trial detention center by the decision of the same Timiryazevsky court.
The defense, in turn, appealed the decision of the first instance to the Moscow City Court.
