Props for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records released to TIME magazine, the White House&#39;s decision last month to fly a Marine Corps helicopter to the South Lawn for an event celebrating American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
A green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as &quot;Marine One&quot; when the president is on board, was the centerpiece of a July 17 event at the White House that showcased US construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White House officials toured technology products from all fifty states.
The Connecticut-built helicopter was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi forklift.
According to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter operations, the White House Military Department ordered the helicopter&#39;s presence in a private order, or &quot;FRAGO&quot;, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn. on the occasion of an &quot;unusual&quot; event.
&quot;I just wanted you to make sure you&#39;re in the know because this is an unusual high-profile event,&quot; the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Marine Corps Air Force First Deputy Chief, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 for a 3 p.m. event and remain there until the lawn was vacated between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. that day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight, subject to business hours restrictions.
The first crew escorted the helicopter throughout the event, and the unit&#39;s security guards remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event was in violation of this ruling.
“Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of the Hatch Law, and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The &quot;Made in America&quot; event was declared an official event by the White House and was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance health care reform, which was then in the process of being drafted in the Senate, and touted attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as &quot;Marine One&quot; and &quot;Air Force One&quot; for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But requesting them solely for the sake of a photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump had already been the subject of controversy in February, when a presidential jet passed in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was inundated with messages complaining about his predecessor&#39;s use of the presidential jet.
&quot;The White House is thrilled with the Made in America display, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,&quot; said Lindsey Walters, Deputy White House Press Secretary.
HMX-1 crews often fly around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to practice transporting the President of the United States to the White House to the nearest inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 practice landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight performed for the &quot;Made in America&quot; event was credited to the crew towards the required training flights for the month.
The unit&#39;s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of &quot;non-presidential support missions.&quot;
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesperson said the company was not involved in organizing the helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep track of the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the DoD hourly rates for Fiscal Year 2017, the DoD reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records recorded the aircraft&#39;s time in the air as 30 minutes each way from its home base at Marine Corps Air Station Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on an estimated refund rate is completely wrong,” Walters says.
&quot;These approximate rates include personnel, maintenance and many other sunk costs that are included in the annual appropriations.&quot;
According to a 2015 study by the RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do include the cost of fuel, maintenance, and contracted expenses.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in defense of using a helicopter for the event.
&quot;The idea is to showcase American made stuff this week,&quot; Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
So, of course, it is perfectly appropriate to pay attention to it.”
It was unclear if Trump was interacting with the helicopter as he surveyed the South Lawn during the event, but he certainly sat in the driver&#39;s seat of a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives, joking with the press about his own fleet of the company&#39;s products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said. “I have three of them.”
